# Linkrowth code structure

> Working reference. Canonical detail lives in `SPEC.md` §8.

## Tree (Episode 1 target)

```
linkrowth/
├── src/
│   ├── engage.ts        # core engage() — stable public API
│   ├── cli.ts           # thin CLI consumer of engage()
│   ├── prompts.ts       # typed prompt builders; no API calls
│   ├── llm.ts           # provider-agnostic call(); routes via env
│   ├── types.ts         # Post, UserContext, EngageResult, LlmRequest, …
│   ├── config/
│   │   └── env.ts       # .env loading, provider selection, API keys
│   └── clients/
│       ├── claude.ts    # Anthropic — stub until needed
│       ├── gpt.ts       # OpenAI — Episode 1 default
│       ├── gemini.ts    # Google Gemini — implemented
│       └── kimi.ts      # Kimi / Moonshot — stub until needed
├── config/
│   ├── user.json        # gitignored
│   └── user.example.json
├── package.json
├── tsconfig.json
└── README.md
```

## Data flow

```
cli.ts
  └─► engage.ts
        ├─► types.ts
        ├─► prompts.ts     buildEngagePrompt(post, context)
        └─► llm.ts         call(request)
              └─► clients/gpt.ts       (Episode 1 default)
              └─► clients/gemini.ts
              └─► clients/claude.ts    (future)
              └─► clients/kimi.ts     (future)
```

## Module rules

| Module | Owns | Must not |
|---|---|---|
| `engage.ts` | orchestration: context → prompt → LLM → result | provider SDKs, prompt strings |
| `prompts.ts` | `{ system, user }` builders | API calls, side effects |
| `llm.ts` | `call()` entry, provider routing, shared defaults | HTTP, SDK imports |
| `clients/*.ts` | one provider's SDK/HTTP + `call()` | business logic, prompts |
| `cli.ts` | stdin/argv, print output | anything else |
| `types.ts` | shared interfaces | implementation |

## Client contract

Every file in `clients/` exports the same shape:

```typescript
import type { LlmRequest } from "../types";

export async function call(request: LlmRequest): Promise<string>
```

`llm.ts` is the only module that imports from `clients/`.  
`engage.ts` and above import `call` from `llm.ts` only.

## Episode 1 scope

- Ship `clients/gpt.ts` and `clients/gemini.ts`
- `claude.ts` / `kimi.ts` remain stubs until a provider switch is needed
- Provider selection via `LINKROWTH_PROVIDER` in `.env` (see `.env.example`)
- Only the active provider's API key is required at runtime
- `validateEnv()` runs at CLI startup for fail-fast errors

## Environment variables

Copy `.env.example` to `.env` (never commit `.env`):

| Variable | Required | Description |
|---|---|---|
| `LINKROWTH_PROVIDER` | No | `openai` (default), `gemini`, `anthropic`, `kimi` |
| `OPENAI_API_KEY` | If provider=openai | OpenAI API key |
| `GEMINI_API_KEY` | If provider=gemini | Google AI Studio key |
| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | If provider=anthropic | Anthropic API key |
| `KIMI_API_KEY` | If provider=kimi | Moonshot / Kimi API key |
| `LINKROWTH_*_MODEL` | No | Override default model per provider |
